And the Rev'd James Castley, Clerk of the 3rd part - By which articles after reciting (inter alia) that Dissentions had arisen between the said Tho's Pain & Elizabeth his wife, & that they had agreed to live separate. And also reciting the Will of the said Sam'l Ollive & that the sd. Thomas Pain had agreed that the Sd Elizabrth should have & take her share of the sd. Monies of the sd. House when the same should become due and payable & that he would give any Discharge that should then be required[?] to & for the use of the sd. Elizabeth The sd. Tho's Pain did covenant to permit the sd. Elizabeth to live seperaet from him & to carry on such Trade & Business as she should think fit, notwithstanding her Coverture & as if she were a Femme Sole. An that he would not at any time thereafter claim or demand the sd. Monies which she should be entitled to at the time of the sale of the sd. 'House in Lewes aforesaid, or any of the Monies Rings Plate Cloathes Linen Woolen Household Goiods or Stock in Trade which the sd. Elizabeth should or might at any time thereafter buy or purchase or which should be devised or given to her or she would otehrwise acquire & that she should & might enjoy & absolutely dipose of the same as if she were a Femme Sole & unmarried.' fields.short_title: Letter to Mdm. Bonneville
fields.title: Letter to Mdm. Bonneville
fields.physical_description: 4pg. One leaf folded over; two pages written on, one for address. Has remnant of red wax seal and postmark for 'WASH CITY.' Written in a somewhat shaky hand.
fields.other_description: My dear madam and my dear boys,I this moment received your lettter with great pleasure for I was anxious for your safety on the passage as the weather with us was several times stormy. You enclose[sic] me a bill for £22.10s sterling payable to Capt. Stanley for the balance of your passage so tell me in what manner I shall remit the money to him and it shall be done immediately. I have written to Col. Kirkbride of Bordon town in the state of New Jersey who will expect your coming there, and from whom you will receive every friendship. I expect to be there myself in about a month or five weeks. If you are in wants of money to continue your journey to Bordontown I will be obliged to any of my friends in Norfolk to supplu you and I will remit it to them as soon as I am informed of it. I can depend on your oeconomy in the use of it, and you and the poor boys can rest upon my friendship. I am not personally acquainted with Col. Newton of Norfolk but I find he is a friend of Mr. Maddison[sic] the secretatry of state, and if Col. Newton will be so kind as to supply you with what money you may want I will repay it immediately into the hands of Mr. Maddison or remit it to him thro' the post master.  I suppose your best way will be to come up the bay by the packet to Baltimore and from thence to Philadelphia and Bordon Town. If you should have to stay two or three days at Baltimore enquired for Capt. Clark Bond-street no. 102. It[sic] is the Capt. Of the ship I which I came. I shall write to Mrs. Clark to inform her of your coming. /The letter you have from Mr. Mercier for Mr. Jefferson you can enclose under cover to me either from Norfolk, or more conveniently from Balitmore if you come that way. Mr. Murray a merchnt who several times called upon me at your house in Paris, lives now in Baltimore but I do not know his address. Embrace the poor boys or me and tell them they will soon see me at Bordon-town. I shall write again, to Col. Kirkbride to inform him of your arrival. Your sincere affectionate friend, Thoams PaineAddressed to: Mrs. Bonnevilleat Mrs. Hunt's Boarding houseNo. 127 Main-streetNorfolk Virginia

fields.physical_description: Pair cased watch- Currently held up by some fishing wire and the case is released from the watch. The cover sits below on a piece of wood. The watch's ace is white and had roman numeral numbers for the hour along with numbers for the minutes- 5 through 60, counted by 5s.  With the exception of the roman numeral MI, the writing is in script. The front case has a makers mark that appears to date it to 1765. There also appears to be an HK or HR maker mark and 77 as well but I cannot identify it at this point. The back case also has a makers mark.
fields.other_description: The front case of the watch says, 'Thos. Paine 1769' and 'MI' The watch is stopped at the time, 11 o'clock. The back case does not have an inscription on it, but the watch mechanism does- it says, 'Thos. Wagstaffe London N 5107'; The description from the existing list says, 'English Pair Cased Watch   of Sterling/Gilt Mounted in Glass Domed Custom Stand with Mirror to Reflect Inner Workings; By Watch Maker Thomas Wagstaffe with Verge Escapement; Working Bear Name of Watch Maker, Londdon, And #5107; The Outer Case With Thomas' Paine's Name In Script and Dated 1769 (The Letter MI Added); The Face of White Enamel With Roman Numerals for Hours and Arabic Numbers for Second (Bears London Hallmarks 1765); 18 Inches High Overall Encased. Watch 1 3/4 Inch Diameter. Presented By Dr. W. Barclay Stephens of California. NOTE. Thomas Wagstaffe was an Important Watch Maker Between 1756-93. Examples of His Watches are found in many leading collections around the world'  In provenance records, letter from Stephens to the TPNHA about the watch. He said he believed it to be Thomas Paine's watch and bought it from an antique dealer in Rochester, who did not have additional information about it. The letter also says that watch has a print of Paine inside it, but that is no longer there.
